The issue lies in the `inr` case of the proof for `example {A B : Islander} (hAB : A said (A.isKnave or B.isKnave)) : A.isKnight and B.isKnave := by ...`.
The original code uses `knight_or_knave A with hA hA` followed by `obtain hA | hA := A.isKnight_or_isKnave`.
This means:
- In the `inl` case, `hA` is `A.isKnight`.
- In the `inr` case, `hA` is `A.isKnave`.

The error occurs in the `inr` case. Let's look at the relevant part of the code:

```tactics
--  --knight_or_knave A with hA hA
--  --obtain hA | hA := A.isKnight_or_isKnave
--  --· obtain hA' | hB := knight_said hAB hA
--  --  · exfalso
--  --    have hContr : ¬(Island. isKnave A ∨ Island. isKnave B) := by tauto
--  --    tauto
--  --  · exact ⟨hA, hB⟩
--  --· exfalso
--  --  have hContr : ¬(Island. isKnave A ∨ Island. isKnave B) := by tauto
--  --  tauto
```
When `hA` is `A.isKnave` (the `inr` case), `hAB` is `A said (A.isKnave ∨ B.isKnave)`.
So `knight_said hAB hA` (where `hA` is `A.isKnave`) is not applicable, because `knight_said` requires the first argument (`A` in `A said P`) to be a knight.
Instead, we should use `knave_said`. So `knave_said hAB hA` (where `hA` is `A.isKnave`) should be used.
`knave_said hAB hA` will give `¬(A.isKnave ∨ B.isKnave)`.
But we also have `this : ¬(A.isKnave ∨ B.isKnave)`.
So we have `¬(A.isKnave ∨ B.isKnave)` from `this` and from `knave_said`.
This means we have `¬(A.isKnave ∨ B.isKnave)` and `A.isKnave`.
This is a contradiction. `A.isKnave` and `¬A.isKnave`.
So we can use `contradiction` or `exfalso` followed by `tauto`.

The suggestion is to replace the `sorry` with a direct proof of the goal using the contradiction.
