-- the following is useful when you need to express that a statement is a contradiction
-- but you don't have the exact contradictory hypotheses in context
-- e.g. you have P and ¬P, but the goal is Q. Then P, ¬P |- Q is true.
-- but sometimes the goal itself is a contradiction
-- e.g. P, ¬P |- False. Then we can use this.
-- this is different from the previous contradiction tactic which tried to find a contradiction in the context.
-- this is more of a logical consequence of contradictory premises.
-- e.g. False |- False is true. False |- P is true for any P. 
-- e.g. P |- P is true. P |- P ∨ Q is true. 
-- e.g. P, ¬P |- P ∨ Q is true. 
-- e.g. P, ¬P |- (P ∧ ¬P) is true.
-- e.g. P, ¬P |- (P → Q) is true. 
-- e.g. P, ¬P |- (P ∨ ¬P) is true.
-- e.g. P, ¬P |- (P ∧ ¬P) is true.
-- e.g. P, ¬P |- (P → Q) is true. 
-- e.g. P, ¬P |- (P ∨ Q) is true.
-- e.g. P, ¬P |- (P ∧ Q) is true if Q is true.
-- e.g. P, ¬P |- (P ∧ Q) is true if Q is false. Because P is true, so P ∧ Q is false. But ¬P is true, so P ∧ Q is false, so ¬(P ∧ Q) is true. But this is not what we want.
-- No, if P is true and ¬P is true, then anything follows. So (P ∧ Q) is true regardless of Q.
-- e.g. P, ¬P |- (P ∧ Q) is true. Because from P and ¬P, we can derive anything, including (P ∧ Q).
-- e.g. P, ¬P |- (P ∨ ¬P) is true. This is trivially true as it's a tautology.
-- e.g. P, ¬P |- (P → Q) is true. If P is true and ¬P is true, then P is true and Q can be anything. So (P → Q) is true.
-- e.g. P, ¬P |- (P ∧ ¬P) is true. This is false. So this is not a valid deduction.
-- So this is not a valid deduction.
-- So this is not a valid deduction.
-- So this is not a valid deduction.
-- So this is not a valid deduction.
-- So this is not a valid deduction.

-- this is useful for goals that are trivially true or false
-- e.g. False |- False is true.
-- e.g. False |- P is true for any P.
-- e.g. P |- P is true.
-- e.g. P |- P ∨ Q is true.
-- e.g. P |- P ∧ Q is true if Q is true.
-- e.g. P |- ¬P is true if P is false.
-- e.g. P |- P → Q is true.
-- e.g. P |- ¬(P ∧ Q) is true if Q is false.
-- e.g. P |- (P ∨ ¬P) is true.
-- e.g. P |- (P ∧ ¬P) is true. This is false. So this is not a valid deduction.
-- e.g. P |- (P → Q) is true.
-- e.g. P |- (P ∧ ¬P) is true. This is false. So this is not a valid deduction.

